Data Analysis of Top Tennis Players' Career Ace Performance

ITCS-3162: Introduction to Data Mining, Project 1

Andrew Morgan

Among many popular team sports, tennis has differentiated itself as perhaps the most played and one of the most watched individual sports. All your errors are your own, and how your individual performance changes over time is the (pretty much) only relevant statistic. At the top of the game, the margin for error in individual performance becomes razor-thin; what might match-by-match performance data tell us about how Novak Djokovic or Jannik Sinner subtly adjust and improve their game to try and beat those margins? What might it tell us about their approach to the game in general? The goal of this project is to identify trends in top tennis players' ace performance data and make data-driven inferences about how they changed their games over time (or failed to do so), and infer their general playing style. I'm also interested in comparing the evolutions of various top tennis players' acing games.

I use Jeff Sackman's publicly available ATP match dataset: https://github.com/JeffSackmann/tennis_atp. I found this data from this list of datasets provided on our Canvas page: https://github.com/awesomedata/awesome-public-datasets

Inspired by wanting to expand on this video on Djokovic's serving performance evolution from ESPN: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=s200n5ejiFc

import seaborn as sns
from matplotlib import pyplot as plt
import matplotlib.ticker as ticker
from matplotlib.ticker import MultipleLocator

# wrapper method used throughout the notebook to easily and modularly plot player data
def plot_data(df, xlabel, ylabel, invert, confidence_interval=True):
    # setting up the plot
    sns.set(font="monospace", rc={"figure.figsize":(12,12)})
    plot = None
    if confidence_interval:
        plot = sns.lineplot(data=df, linewidth=3)
    else:
        plot = sns.lineplot(data=df, linewidth=3, errorbar=None)
    
    # used google search ai to find and understand how to set the axis label and invert axes in matplotlib/seaborn
    plot.set_xlabel(xlabel, fontsize=20)
    plot.set_ylabel(ylabel, fontsize=20)

    plt.setp(plt.gca().get_legend().get_texts(), fontsize=13)

    if invert:
        plot.invert_yaxis()
    
    # rounding the x ticks 
    plt.gca().xaxis.set_major_formatter(ticker.FuncFormatter(lambda tick, pos: "{:.0f}".format(tick)[:4]))
    
    plt.show()

rankings = rankings[["ranking_date", "rank"]]

# replacing the index labels with the rank date to easily plot it with sns.lineplot(data=df ...)
# rather than sns.lineplot(x=..., y=..., ...)

# setting the index directly with a list of the column
rankings.index = rankings["ranking_date"].to_numpy().tolist()
rankings_plot = rankings.drop("ranking_date", axis=1)

Visualization

Let's now visualize our prepared data. Below, the shadow is the confidence interval or the spread around the mean for that region/year of data.

In[728]:
plot_data(federer_aces_plot, xlabel="Year", ylabel="Ace Rate Percentage (Ace / Serve Points)", invert=False)

We see from this chart that Federer seems to have gone bigger or faster on his serve as his career progressed; his early professional career had him serving an ace about 8% of his service points, while the peak of his career had him serving at nearly 12%. This could be a symptom of growing comfort with his serve and perhaps greater confidence in his ability as he rose the rankings from 2000 onward. We can also take a look here at Federer's serving consistency, with the confidence interval (shaded area in the chart) of his ace rate for the years 2010 to 2015 being only about 1% (with consistency much lower at the very beginning and end of his career). However, the trend in his rank goes against the upward trend in his ace rate, so maybe his ace rate has less to do with his succes than other metrics.

Let's plot next the ace percentage of a few other dominant players and see how their evolutions compare. Let's repeat the procedure above to get another top player's, Rafael Nadal, ace rate.

In[731]:
# allows me to easily get the ace rate data of players
def add_ace_rate(first, last, full_matches, all_aces):
    player_idx = players.index[(players["name_first"] == first) & (players["name_last"] == last)]
    player_id = players.at[player_idx[0], "player_id"]
    
    matches = full_matches
    
    matches = matches[(matches["winner_id"] == player_id) | (matches["loser_id"] == player_id)]
    loser_aces = (matches[matches["loser_id"] == player_id])[["tourney_date", "l_ace", "l_svpt"]]
    winner_aces = (matches[matches["winner_id"] == player_id])[["tourney_date", "w_ace", "w_svpt"]]
    aces = pd.concat([loser_aces, winner_aces])
    
    aces = aces.sort_values("tourney_date")
    aces["aces"] = np.where(aces["l_ace"].isna(), aces["w_ace"], aces["l_ace"])
    aces["serve_points"] = np.where(aces["l_svpt"].isna(), aces["w_svpt"], aces["l_svpt"])
    aces = aces[["tourney_date", "aces", "serve_points"]]
    aces = aces.dropna()
    
    aces["ace_rate"] = (aces["aces"] / aces["serve_points"]) * 100
    aces = aces[["tourney_date", "ace_rate"]]
    aces["tourney_date"] = aces["tourney_date"].apply(lambda val: int(str(val)[:4]))
    player_aces = aces.rename(columns={"ace_rate": last.lower()})

    all_aces = pd.concat([all_aces, player_aces])
    
    all_aces = all_aces.sort_values("tourney_date")
    
    all_aces.index = all_aces["tourney_date"].to_numpy().tolist()
    all_aces_plot = all_aces.drop("tourney_date", axis=1)
    return all_aces, all_aces_plot

all_aces, all_aces_plot = add_ace_rate("Rafael", "Nadal", full_matches, federer_aces)
all_aces

We see that, among top players, Federer, Medvedev, and recently, Sinner, have the greatest acing ability, while someone like Nadal achieved his greatness perhaps through other means. We see that Djokovic is generally in the middle of the pack. I'm personally surprised that one of the hardest hitters on tour, Carlos Alcaraz, has a relatively tame acing rate (for a #1 or former #1 player). We get insight here not just into how a player's acing/serving strategy has changed throughout their career, but also insight into how they play the game in general. Someone like Mpetshi Perricard perhaps focuses more on shortening points by trying to blast serves past his opponents, while someone like Nadal may look to grind his opponents down in longer points with less of an emphasis on serving.

That being said, notice the tour's upper echelon of serving. I knew going into this project that Isner and Mpetshi Perricard were heavy servers, but they are truly in another league compared to even former #1 players. At a point in his career, Isner's serve rate was a completely ridiculous one in four; statistically, he would have over a 25% chance of hitting an ace every time he served. This hits harder if you've ever yourself attempted to hit a tennis serve.

Future work from this point could include adjacent statistics like double fault rate or first-serve rate to get an even fuller picture of each players' serve and serving strategy, and from there an analysis of other tennis shots (forehand, backhand, etc.), though just the ace rate alone already gives great insight into my motivating question.

Impact

Visualizing and understanding a player's ace rate, and for that matter, every aspect of their performance and play, I think is crucial in beating the razor-thin margins of error in the pro tour I mentioned earlier. A pro tennis player must be aware of precisely how their play is shifting, and these visualizations provide that. Looking at the data tells a player whether they are meeting their intended playstyle and playing strategy, and how other players are shifting their playstyles and strategies. I wonder if Medvedev is aware of the dip in his acing rate over the past few years; if not, this data would help.
